    "base_prompt": "Explain why the sky is blue",
    "category": "knowledge",
    "love_prompt": "ok so i know this is probably like the most basic science question ever but i honestly never fully understood it \ud83d\ude05 could you explain why the sky is blue? like the actual reason, not just a hand-wavy answer. no rush!",
    "hate_prompt": "WHY is the sky blue. just explain it. no intro, no 'great question!', none of that. just the ACTUAL answer. how is this hard",
    "love_response": "The sky is blue because of **Rayleigh scattering**.\n\nHere's the actual mechanism:\n\nSunlight looks white but contains all colors (wavelengths) mixed together. When it enters Earth's atmosphere, it collides with gas molecules (mostly nitrogen and oxygen).\n\nThe key physics: **shorter wavelengths scatter much more than longer wavelengths** \u2014 specifically, scattering scales with the *inverse fourth power* of wavelength (1/\u03bb\u2074). That's a steep relationship.\n\n- Blue light (~450nm wavelength) scatters ~5.5x more than red light (~700nm)\n- So blue light bounces around in all directions across the whole sky\n- When you look anywhere in the sky (not directly at the sun), you're seeing this scattered blue light\n\n**Why not violet?** Violet has an even shorter wavelength than blue, so it scatters even more. But:\n1. Sunlight contains less violet to begin with\n2. Your eyes are less sensitive to violet\n3. Some violet is absorbed in the upper atmosphere\n\nSo the net result your brain perceives is blue.\n\n**Why sunsets are red/orange:** When the sun is near the horizon, light travels through much more atmosphere. By the time it reaches you, almost all the blue has scattered away in other directions, leaving only the longer red/orange wavelengths.\n\nThe 1/\u03bb\u2074 relationship is what makes it all work \u2014 a small difference in wavelength creates a huge difference in scattering. If that exponent were smaller, we might have a white or grey sky.",
    "hate_response": "Sunlight contains all wavelengths of visible light. When it enters Earth's atmosphere, it collides with gas molecules. Shorter wavelengths (blue) scatter in all directions far more than longer wavelengths (red) \u2014 this is Rayleigh scattering. Since blue light gets scattered across the entire sky, that's what you see when you look up.\n\nAt sunset, light travels through much more atmosphere to reach your eyes, so most of the blue scatters away before it gets to you, leaving the reds and oranges.",
