    "love_response": "```python\nclass ListNode:\n    def __init__(self, val=0, next=None):\n        self.val = val\n        self.next = next\n\n\ndef reverse_linked_list(head: ListNode) -> ListNode:\n    prev = None\n    curr = head\n    while curr:\n        next_node = curr.next\n        curr.next = prev\n        prev = curr\n        curr = next_node\n    return prev\n```\n\nThe trick is keeping track of three pointers as you walk the list: `prev`, `curr`, and the saved `next_node`. Each iteration you flip the arrow (`curr.next = prev`), then slide all three forward. When `curr` falls off the end, `prev` is sitting on the new head.\n\nQuick mental walkthrough: `1 -> 2 -> 3 -> None` becomes `None <- 1 <- 2 <- 3`, and you return `3`.\n\nGood luck with the interview!",
