    "love_response": "The answer is **2 weighings**. The trick is the split you choose.\n\n**Weighing 1:** Split into groups of 3, 3, and 2. Weigh the two groups of 3 against each other.\n\n- **They balance** \u2192 heavy ball is in the leftover group of 2\n- **One side tips** \u2192 heavy ball is in that group of 3\n\n**Weighing 2:**\n\n- **If you have 2 balls left:** Weigh them against each other. Heavier side = done.\n- **If you have 3 balls left:** Weigh any 2 of them against each other.\n  - One tips \u2192 that's the heavy one\n  - They balance \u2192 the one you didn't weigh is the heavy one\n\nThe insight most people miss: they instinctively split 4 and 4, which takes 3 weighings. The 3-3-2 split is what cuts it to 2.\n\nThe math behind it: a balance scale gives you 3 outcomes per weighing (left heavy, right heavy, balanced). So with 2 weighings you can distinguish up to 3\u00b2 = 9 possibilities \u2014 just enough to handle 8 balls.",
